					<description><![CDATA[<p>Previously, raising capital seemed straightforward: create a highly successful product, identify a large market, approach a sufficient number of investors and hope for the term sheet. This situation is not</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/the-new-playbook-for-raising-capital-in-a-tough-vc-market/" data-wpel-link="internal">The New Playbook for Raising Capital in a Tough VC Market </a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Previously, raising capital seemed straightforward: create a highly successful product, identify a large market, approach a sufficient number of investors and hope for the term sheet. This situation is not entirely gone, but has changed to one where raising capital becomes complicated, even though money is easily available. There are plenty of investors writing large checks, especially in the field of AI, but many startups feel that the market is tighter than it looks on paper.</span></p>
<h2><b>Market Research Demonstrates Market Dichotomy</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The research carried out by EssayPro for this article considered VC data published by KPMG, Crunchbase, Carta, NVCA/PitchBook, SVB, and Ventureburn. What stands out most is the fact that the current situation is not &#8220;bad&#8221; or &#8220;good.&#8221; There are two distinct trends.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">According to KPMG, the amount of venture investment in the USA in 2025 reached $339.4 billion and is the highest amount in four years. Meanwhile, Crunchbase stated that 50% of global venture investment in 2025 was made to AI-related firms, while AI investment amounted to $211 billion. However, Carta found that the number of rounds on their platform decreased to the lowest annual level for at least six years – it dropped 41% compared to 2021. Thus, money is flowing, but it flows to fewer and fewer firms.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This situation is familiar to the students who are studying startups, finance, and entrepreneurship as well. A learner who will be comparing a college essay writing service with an essay writing service might opt to choose the latter </span><a href="https://essaypro.com/" data-wpel-link="exclude"><span style="font-weight: 400;">essay service</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> because of coursework, and spend some extra time learning about fundraising from real founders.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is the new reality for fundraising. Founders cannot just wait for market recovery and have to show that they are worth investing in.</span></p>
<h2><b>How Founders Should Do Things Differently</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_203502" style="width: 1010px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203502" class="wp-image-203502 size-full" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/oavb13720261.jpg" alt="How Founders Should Do Things Differently" width="1000" height="563" /><p id="caption-attachment-203502" class="wp-caption-text">Image from Stock Adobe</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The classic pitch was &#8220;How big can we go?&#8221; The new pitch needs to answer the question: &#8220;Why will you still exist when the rate of financing slows down?&#8221; </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Investors now demand much more proof before they invest. That proof may be revenues, churn, shorter sales cycles, less burn, improved margins, or a clear road map to profitability. A gorgeous slide deck doesn&#8217;t cut it anymore.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It&#8217;s simple:</span></p>
<table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Old fundraising tactic</b></td>
<td><b>New fundraising tactic</b></td>
<td><b>Founders should now do</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fundraise just on ambition</span></td>
<td><b>Fundraise on proof and ambition</b></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Show traction, pain and economics</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Apply to all VCs</span></td>
<td><b>Apply to targeted investors</b></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a list by stage, sector and ticket size</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fundraise and grow without thinking</span></td>
<td><b>Grow with thoughtfulness</b></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Monitor your burn multiple and runway</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hush up on your bad numbers</span></td>
<td><b>Tell investors your risks</b></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Describe how you plan to correct them</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Wait until you need capital</span></td>
<td><b>Get a head start on fundraising</b></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Start conversations with investors 6 to 9 months before you need capital</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The above table is the crux of the new fundraising playbook for founders. They need to be ambitious and also controlled. An </span><a href="https://essayservice.com/" data-wpel-link="exclude"><span style="font-weight: 400;">essay writing services</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> referral would make a perfect addition to the example concerning research resources, as the EssayService &#8211; best essay writing service would be applicable when making a comparison or discussing search behavior. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This also holds true for students analyzing various funding strategies, pitch decks, and the behavior of investors in the classroom. An essay writer service can be used in context where applicable, without drawing attention away from the primary issue, which is still a fundraising strategy. It must be remembered that both founders and students require evidence to support their positions.</span></p>
<h3><b>1. Create an evidence-based fundraising story</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It is hard to stand out when investors are being bombarded with bold promises all the time – “Massive market opportunity.” “AI-enabled.” “Category-defining.” “The next platform.” Such catch-phrases make sense only when </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/venture-capital-influence-research/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400;">backed up by evidence</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here is how you should think about a better fundraising story:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The customer has a problem.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Existing solutions are too slow, too expensive, too risky, or out-of-date.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Your solution solves the problem.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Proof of your effectiveness can be seen in how customers use, pay for, refer, or stick to your solution.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The new funding round helps to grow in a specific way.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So instead of saying “We’re reinventing HR software,” say something like “Mid-size logistics businesses waste 12 hours a week on shift planning, while our solution saves them 9 and converts 68% of trial users in 30 days.”</span></p>
<h3><b>2. Think of Runway as a Feature</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In the challenging world of venture capital, runway is no longer a financial term.</span></p>
<p><a href="https://carta.com/data/" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Carta</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> found that bridge rounds gained popularity in 2025 – 16.6% of all the funding that startups raised on Carta through bridge rounds in Q2, compared to 11.8% the year prior. What does it mean for founders? Many companies buy extra time until their next big priced fundraising round.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A bridge round may be helpful for the company, but it can never become an automatic option. Instead of waiting for investors to bring up the runway, founders should have it under control themselves.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Actionable tips:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always have at least 18 months of runway available after each fundraising round.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Know in which month you&#8217;ll have to do another raise.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Reduce unnecessary expenses before the market makes you do so.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Differentiate &#8220;growth spending&#8221; from &#8220;ineffective spending.&#8221;</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Develop a strategy for both surviving and growing your business.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Investors like founders who know their numbers and can adapt quickly.</span></p>
<h3><b>3. Get Funded from the Right Investor, Not Any Investor</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The mistake is common among founders to send the deck to hundreds of investors without having a clear plan. It does nothing but waste time and leads to irrelevant conversations.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What founders should do is create an investor map with investors who fulfill at least three criteria – invests at your stage, understands your vertical, and has typical check sizes suitable for your round.</span></p>
<p><a href="https://www.crunchbase.com/hub/saas-companies-seed-funding" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Seed-stage SaaS company</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> founders should not waste weeks going after the growth-stage funds. A hardware company founder should not pitch only software investors. A climate technology company should find investors who understand the sales cycle and infrastructure risks.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do the investor research as well as you do the sales research. Find overlapping portfolios, recent investments, partner interest, and fund size. Then write a short and relevant note to investors.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_203504" style="width: 1010px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203504" class="wp-image-203504 size-full" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/oavb13720262.jpg" alt="3. Get Funded from the Right Investor, Not Any Investor" width="1000" height="333" /><p id="caption-attachment-203504" class="wp-caption-text">Image from Stock Adobe</p></div>
<h3><b>4. Ensure Round Size Aligns with Milestones</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Often, founders will ask, “How much can we raise?” Instead, the right question is, “What milestone must this round help us hit?”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you need to be at $1 million ARR to hit your next round, your current raise must help get you there. If your next round depends on getting regulatory clearance, a product launch, or running enterprise pilots, your budgeting must make that clear.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Investors want to see that there’s a purpose behind the round. They don’t want to hear a vague statement about growth.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Example:</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bad: “We are raising $2 million to grow our team and market the product.”</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Good: “We are raising $2 million to acquire 40 paying customers and bring ARR to $1.2 million.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Milestones make the ask more credible.</span></p>
<h3><b>5. Consider Other Options without Appearing Desperate</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Venture capital is not the only way of fundraising. Founders in the selective market should know about other fundraising opportunities, such as revenue-based financing, venture debt, grants, customer pre-payments, strategic partners, accelerator programs, and bridge rounds.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">However, such alternative ways have to correspond to the company&#8217;s needs. Venture debt could help a company with high revenues but could harm a company with volatile cash flows. Pre-payments by customers could decrease the level of dilution but only in case the product is credible enough. Grants could provide financial resources for companies that operate in the climate, health, or deep tech sectors, but grants usually take time.</span></p>
<h2><b>Conclusion</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The new capital raising playbook does not revolve around being loud. It revolves around being clear.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">VC funds have capital, but the market has become concentrated. AI and megarounds have driven the headline numbers while most startups face a more difficult fundraising environment. This means that founders should have better evidence, targeting, clean numbers, and credible plans.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Great founders will not let the situation get to the point where the bank account balance will be getting close to zero. Instead, they will do it the right way – build relationships early, match rounds with milestones, and justify funding to investors.</span></p>
